# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] The **10th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1807, to March 4, 1809, during the seventh and eighth years of Thomas Jefferson's presidency.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 census; both chambers had an overwhelming Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, and 1 interim appointment.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 4 resignations, 4 deaths, and 2 vacancies from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Democratic-Republicans had no net change and Federalists picked up 2 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/10th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] The **11th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1809, to March 4, 1811, during the first two years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1814; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1810; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1812.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] There were 8 resignations, 2 deaths, 1 interim appointment, and 1 vacancy from before this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/11th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 12 resignations, 1 death, and 1 change due to a contested election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1777 New York gubernatorial election** was held in June 1777 to elect the governor and the lieutenant governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The election began on June 1, but due to the American Revolution it took some time to collect and count the votes, and the official result was announced on July 9.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] George Clinton accepted the office of Governor on July 11 and assumed its duties immediately, pending to take the oath as soon as he could safely leave his military command.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] There were no parties yet, as the Democratic-Republican and Federalist Parties appeared only in 1792.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Until then the candidacies were based on personal recognition.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The concepts of "running mates" also did not apply in this election, with candidates running separately for Governor and Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The New York Committee of Safety endorsed Philip Schuyler for Governor and George Clinton for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] George Clinton was elected both Governor and Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton formally resigned the lieutenant governorship, leaving a vacancy.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] State Senator Pierre Van Cortlandt was elected *President pro tempore* of the State Senate, and acted as Lieutenant Governor until the end of the legislative year.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Van Cortlandt was then elected in a special election and took office as Lieutenant Governor on June 30, 1778.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in New York from April 29 to May 1, 1783.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] George Clinton, the incumbent governor, defeated Philip Schuyler, the surveyor general, and Ephraim Paine, the senator from the middle district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In March 1783, the New York legislature repealed the act granting all import duties to the United States government under the Articles of Confederation.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In its place, the legislature passed a law granting such duties but restricting their collection and reserving the power of appointment of collecting officers to the state of New York.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The tariff duties issue, along with the ongoing debate over the new Constitution of the United States, formed the basis for the early development of political factions in the state.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The import duties, which were incredibly valuable given the prominence of the Port of New York City, formed the basis of a larger debate over the nature of New York's sovereignty and association with the other independent American states.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The nationalist faction, which supported the unrestricted grant of duties to the United States, was led by Alexander Hamilton, John Jay, Robert R.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Livingston, Philip Schuyler, and the Van Rensselaer family.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The opposition was led by Governor George Clinton, who had served in the state's highest office since its establishment following the Revolution with little opposition, having been returned unanimously in 1780.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] His supporters included Robert Yates, John Lansing, and Melancton Smith.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] These factions are informally known as the Federalists and anti-Federalists, respectively.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1789 New York gubernatorial election** was held in April 1789 to elect the Governor of New York for a term beginning in July 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor George Clinton was narrowly re-elected to a fifth consecutive term in office over Robert Yates.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] From the establishment of an independent government of New York in 1777, George Clinton had continuously served in the office of Governor; he had no opponent in 1780 or 1786.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] During that previous decade, New York politics had coalesced around two loose factions: a federalist faction led by Alexander Hamilton, John Jay, Robert R.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Livingston, Philip Schuyler, and the Van Rensselaer family, which favored adoption of the proposed United States Constitution and an anti-federalist faction led by Governor Clinton, Robert Yates, John Lansing, and Melancton Smith, which opposed ratification without serious revision.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At the New York convention to ratify the Constitution in 1788, Clinton presided over a sharp division between the federalists and anti-federalists.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The final vote favored ratification of the Constitution as written by a vote of 30–27.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton, despite his anti-federalist views, closed the convention by vowing to exercise his office to enforce it and maintain order.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] However, partisan divisions were sharpened by the formation of a new national administration under President George Washington, who sought to elevate Hamilton, Jay, and other federalists to his administration without representation for the Clinton faction.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] For the first time, the federalist faction actively organized to block Clinton's re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In light of the incumbent's broad popularity, they sought to nominate an anti-federalist in order to divide the majority faction.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At a meeting in New York City on February 11, they appointed a committee of correspondence to manage the campaign, consisting of Hamilton, William Duer, Robert Troup and anti-federalist Aaron Burr, who defected to oppose Clinton.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The meeting nominated Supreme Court justice Robert Yates.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] On February 24, Yates accepted the nomination.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] There was a movement to nominate Richard Morris, who was favored by the majority within the federalist faction, but he declined to be a candidate on February 27.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Pierre Van Cortlandt was the only candidate for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton was re-elected to a fifth term in office, albeit by the lowest margin to date.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In his home county of Ulster, Clinton won 1,039 out of 1,245 votes.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] However, federalists won a majority of the seats in the New York Assembly.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The **1789 United States House of Representatives elections in New York** were held on March 3 and 4, 1789, to elect 6 U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives to represent the State of New York in the 1st United States Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Constitution on July 26, 1788, by a very slim margin.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On January 27, 1789, the New York State Legislature divided the State of New York into six congressional districts which were not numbered.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Three Federalists and three Anti-Federalists (later known as the Democratic-Republicans) were elected.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Note: This was the first time political parties appeared in the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Before the question of establishing a federal government, or not, arose, all candidatures had been personal.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Now, politicians aligned in two opposing groups: First those in favor of the establishment of a federal government and those against it, and then - after the federal government had been indeed established - those who supported it and those who did not.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The 1st United States Congress had convened at Federal Hall in New York City on March 4, 1789, without any members from the State of New York, and without a quorum in either Senate or House.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The first day with a quorum in the House was April 1.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The representatives elected in and near New York City took their seats soon after the election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The upstate representatives needed some time to arrive, and Peter Silvester took his seat on April 22, John Hathorn on April 23, and Jeremiah Van Rensselaer on May 9.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] In April 1790, all six representatives ran for re-election: Floyd, Hathorn and Van Rensselaer (all Dem.-Rep.) were defeated; Laurance, Benson and Silvester (all Fed.) were re-elected.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The **1789 United States Senate election in New York** was held in July 1789 to elect two U.S. senators to represent the State of New York in the United States Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish the proceedings how to elect the senators.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the First United States Congress for March 4, 1789, and the election of U.S. senators and U.S. representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Both sides expected to win the State election in April.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On June 4, Governor George Clinton called an extra session of the State Legislature to convene on July 6 at City Hall in Albany, New York.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] At the state election in April 1789, for a term beginning on July 1, a large Federalist majority had been elected to the New York State Assembly (65 members), estimated by State Senator James Duane at 42 to 22.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The New York State Senate (24 members) continued with a slim Federalist majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The 13th New York State Legislature (term 1789–90) convened on July 6, and on July 11 passed *"An act directing the manner of electing Senators to represent this State in the Senate of the United States"*, which required the election to be made by "concurrent vote" of both houses of the Legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] This meant, if only one U.S. senator was to be elected, that each house nominated a candidate, and if both houses nominated the same person ("concurred"), the nominee was elected.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] If the Assembly nominated one, the Senate another, then the Senate's nominee was voted upon in the Assembly and the Assembly's nominee in the Senate; if none of the nominees was accepted by the other house, the proceedings started at the beginning.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] If two U.S. senators were to be elected, and Assembly and Senate chose different nominees, then the Assembly should elect one of the two Senate nominees, and the Senate one of the two Assembly nominees, effectively leaving one seat to be filled by each house of the Legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On July 13, the law was submitted to the Council of Revision.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Thus the law was vetoed, and the State Legislature was left to fill the seats without written rules.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] In practice, the Assembly and the Senate separately took a vote, and if the winner in both houses was the same, he was declared elected.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] If Assembly and Senate chose different persons, the houses met for a joint ballot, which occurred for the first time in 1802.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On July 16, after the Council of Revision had vetoed the law, State Senator Philip Schuyler and Assemblyman Rufus King, two Federalists, were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Senate by a joint resolution of both houses of the State Legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments, which consisted of the governor of New York and four state senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the Council.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The **1808 United States House of Representatives elections in New York** were held from April 26 to 28, 1808, to elect 17 U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives to represent the State of New York in the United States House of Representatives of the 11th United States Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] At the same time, a vacancy was filled in the 10th United States Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives had been elected in April 1806 to a term in the 10th United States Congress beginning on March 4, 1807.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] David Thomas had been elected New York State Treasurer in February 1808, and had resigned his seat, leaving a vacancy in the former 12th District.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The other 16 representatives' term would end on March 3, 1809.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The congressional elections were held together with the State elections in late April 1808, about ten months before the term would start on March 4, 1809, and a little more than a year before Congress actually met on May 22, 1809.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] After the U.S. census of 1800, New York's representation in the House was increased to 17 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On March 30, 1802, the New York State Legislature had re-apportioned the congressional districts, dividing New York County seemingly at random into two districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On April 8, 1808, the State Legislature re-apportioned the districts again, separating the 2nd and the 3rd District, and creating two districts with two seats each to be filled on a general ticket: the 2nd and the 6th.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Due to the double-seat districts, there were then only 15 districts; the 16th and 17th were eliminated.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] 9 Democratic-Republicans and 8 Federalists were elected to the 11th Congress, and one Democratic-Republican to fill the vacancy in the 10th Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The incumbents Mumford, Gardenier, Van Rensselaer and Thompson were re-elected; the incumbents Van Alen and Harris were defeated.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Note: The Anti-Federalists called themselves "Republicans." However, at the same time, the Federalists called them "Democrats" which was meant to be pejorative.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Nathan Wilson took his seat in the 10th United States Congress on November 7, 1808.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Mathews took his seat on May 23; Mumford on May 24; and Root on June 7.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] William Denning never took his seat, and resigned.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] A special election to fill the vacancy was held at the annual State election in April 1810, and was won by Samuel L.
